1
00:00:00,619 --> 00:00:04,197
I have an important announcement to make.

2
00:00:04,197 --> 00:00:06,070
What is it? Marriage?

3
00:00:06,070 --> 00:00:07,423
I'm scared.

4
00:00:07,423 --> 00:00:09,413
Why so formal all of a sudden?

5
00:00:09,413 --> 00:00:11,332
I have a bad feeling about this.

6
00:00:11,332 --> 00:00:13,740
I will preemptively oppose.

7
00:00:13,740 --> 00:00:15,836
So, what is it?

8
00:00:16,898 --> 00:00:18,783
[Re-acquiring Tatsuya Kudo]

9
00:00:18,783 --> 00:00:20,992
Huh? Oh, no.

10
00:00:20,992 --> 00:00:23,960
This is a bit...

11
00:00:29,547 --> 00:00:32,069
You've got some nerve, showing up here.

12
00:00:33,446 --> 00:00:35,779
I've brought you good news.

13
00:00:35,779 --> 00:00:37,717
Jesus...

14
00:00:37,717 --> 00:00:41,708
We lost our pitchers to the drug problem,

15
00:00:41,708 --> 00:00:46,288
and Kudo's suspended until autumn
for gambling.

16
00:00:46,288 --> 00:00:47,829
What're you saying you can do?

17
00:00:47,829 --> 00:00:51,659
I will propose a trade to the Vikings.

18
00:00:51,659 --> 00:00:53,287
What?

19
00:00:53,287 --> 00:00:56,451
What? A trade?

20
00:00:57,342 --> 00:01:00,727
You want to trick me again?

21
00:01:00,727 --> 00:01:02,382
Not at all.

22
00:01:05,219 --> 00:01:08,480
Our fans are protesting.

23
00:01:10,569 --> 00:01:13,126
They want us to disband the team.

24
00:01:18,125 --> 00:01:20,909
I get it now.

25
00:01:21,949 --> 00:01:27,006
Sure, why not score some extra players
from a self-destructing team?

26
00:01:27,006 --> 00:01:28,734
That was never my intention.

27
00:01:29,839 --> 00:01:32,346
But I will take responsibility for my actions

28
00:01:32,346 --> 00:01:34,206
by taking Kudo off your hands.

29
00:01:34,206 --> 00:01:35,932
Kudo?

30
00:01:36,444 --> 00:01:40,967
What, you're trading Sawada back to us?

31
00:01:40,967 --> 00:01:42,555
No.

32
00:01:43,615 --> 00:01:46,619
We cannot give up Sawada.

33
00:01:46,619 --> 00:01:49,038
Then who are you trading?

34
00:01:49,038 --> 00:01:50,904
Our pitcher, Suzuki.

35
00:01:50,904 --> 00:01:53,283
Suzuki?

36
00:01:53,808 --> 00:01:56,283
Sure, Suzuki's good.

37
00:01:56,283 --> 00:01:59,064
But I wouldn't say that covers our losses.

38
00:02:00,868 --> 00:02:03,543
And one more.

39
00:02:03,543 --> 00:02:06,627
We will trade Suzuki, and Shohei Matsui.

40
00:02:06,627 --> 00:02:08,587
[#22: Naoya Suzuki - #19: Shohei Matsui]

41
00:02:08,587 --> 00:02:11,683
Matsui is our cleanup hitter in the making.

42
00:02:11,683 --> 00:02:13,913
Hear that?
Are you trying to destroy our future?

43
00:02:13,913 --> 00:02:16,473
Our team has to focus on the now.

44
00:02:16,473 --> 00:02:19,973
If we are to win the series this season,

45
00:02:19,973 --> 00:02:22,851
we need our former,
undisputed cleanup hitter.

46
00:02:22,851 --> 00:02:24,790
We need Tatsuya Kudo.

47
00:02:25,764 --> 00:02:28,762
The Vikings have lost three pitchers.

48
00:02:28,762 --> 00:02:34,145
Suzuki is injury-free, and his pitches
have only grown more powerful.

49
00:02:34,145 --> 00:02:38,659
Matsui is a cleanup hitter
with plenty of potential.

50
00:02:38,659 --> 00:02:42,656
In terms of defense alone,
he already surpasses Kudo.

51
00:02:44,402 --> 00:02:49,489
For the Vikings,
I believe these reinforcements are ideal.

52
00:02:50,477 --> 00:02:53,201
So you say, but still...

53
00:02:53,201 --> 00:02:56,438
By the time the Vikings
return to their peak in two years,

54
00:02:56,438 --> 00:03:00,935
both players will have become
core members of the team.

55
00:03:01,485 --> 00:03:04,246
I understand what you're trying to say.

56
00:03:04,943 --> 00:03:10,340
But Kudo can't play until autumn.

57
00:03:10,340 --> 00:03:12,487
Why are you so determined to get him?

58
00:03:13,919 --> 00:03:15,840
The answer is rather simple.

59
00:03:17,175 --> 00:03:20,149
We are aiming for the Japan Series this year.

60
00:03:22,436 --> 00:03:24,149
Unbelievable.

61
00:03:24,149 --> 00:03:28,643
Therefore, we need a powerful hitter
who can perform well in the autumn.

62
00:03:28,643 --> 00:03:32,032
Does he even want to return to us?

63
00:03:32,032 --> 00:03:35,995
Exactly. I wouldn't even know
how to face the team.

64
00:03:35,995 --> 00:03:38,792
Maybe I'd try a cheeky wink?

65
00:03:38,792 --> 00:03:41,293
- Kudo wouldn't.
- He wouldn't?

66
00:03:41,293 --> 00:03:43,227
It'll be awkward for Sawada as well.

67
00:03:43,227 --> 00:03:45,120
That's right.

68
00:03:45,120 --> 00:03:49,690
We have to really care for our players.

69
00:03:49,690 --> 00:03:51,678
Think of Sawada.

70
00:03:51,678 --> 00:03:53,929
Sawada has already approved the trade.

71
00:03:53,929 --> 00:03:55,869
Say what?

72
00:03:55,869 --> 00:04:00,347
This is a big trade.
I'll need everyone to do their part.

73
00:04:01,286 --> 00:04:03,856
I'm raring to go, Prez.

74
00:04:03,856 --> 00:04:05,974
My shoulders are all warmed up!

75
00:04:08,025 --> 00:04:09,051
Wham!

76
00:04:09,051 --> 00:04:10,364
Thank you.

77
00:04:10,364 --> 00:04:12,322
That's all I get?

78
00:04:12,322 --> 00:04:13,311
What about a hug?

79
00:04:13,311 --> 00:04:14,403
Ouch!

80
00:04:14,403 --> 00:04:15,641
Poor thing.

81
00:04:15,641 --> 00:04:17,047
I protest workplace abuse.

82
00:04:17,047 --> 00:04:18,759
Ow! Ow, ow, ow!

83
00:04:19,966 --> 00:04:21,331
Alright.

84
00:04:22,695 --> 00:04:24,325
I hear you.

85
00:04:26,200 --> 00:04:27,599
But...

86
00:04:28,335 --> 00:04:32,983
the Dreams aren't the only ones
who want Kudo.

87
00:04:36,630 --> 00:04:38,793
The Pelicans are here to join the fray.

88
00:04:43,501 --> 00:04:44,896
Hello there.

89
00:04:47,981 --> 00:04:51,986
Unlike the Dreams,
autumn is a busy season for us.

90
00:04:51,986 --> 00:04:56,372
We train for both the Climax,
and Japan series.

91
00:04:56,372 --> 00:04:59,135
The Pelicans are the ones who need Kudo.

92
00:04:59,135 --> 00:05:01,262
Our goals are one and the same.

93
00:05:01,924 --> 00:05:05,967
We need Kudo to win the series.

94
00:05:08,041 --> 00:05:11,757
The Dreams, notorious for finishing last?
Win a series?

95
00:05:12,999 --> 00:05:15,392
Alright.

96
00:05:15,392 --> 00:05:16,710
How about this?

97
00:05:17,799 --> 00:05:21,133
We'll auction off Tatsuya Kudo.

98
00:05:22,562 --> 00:05:27,315
The Dreams are offering
Naoya Suzuki and Shohei Matsui.

99
00:05:29,390 --> 00:05:32,327
A trade focused on future potential?

100
00:05:33,261 --> 00:05:35,747
Is that really what you need now?

101
00:05:37,204 --> 00:05:41,735
The Pelicans will offer players
who will show immediate results.

102
00:05:41,735 --> 00:05:44,373
We'll trade Ichijo,
who pitched us 8 winning games,

103
00:05:44,373 --> 00:05:47,016
and our outfielder, Todoroki.

104
00:05:47,975 --> 00:05:50,028
That's a solid set of players.

105
00:05:50,028 --> 00:05:53,982
Ichijo is 34 years old, while Todoroki is 33.

106
00:05:53,982 --> 00:05:56,553
Though both are capable players
in their own right,

107
00:05:56,553 --> 00:06:01,471
neither are as enticing
as the young Suzuki, or Matsui.

108
00:06:03,487 --> 00:06:05,867
You clearly don't understand.

109
00:06:07,379 --> 00:06:11,316
There are only 12 GMs
in the Japanese league.

110
00:06:11,316 --> 00:06:13,047
12.

111
00:06:13,047 --> 00:06:15,614
It's an incredibly coveted role.

112
00:06:15,614 --> 00:06:17,573
Let's not talk about this now.

113
00:06:17,573 --> 00:06:22,819
The position of GM is an honor.
You ought to protect it with your life.

114
00:06:23,846 --> 00:06:26,832
If you want to negotiate,
stop deceiving your opponent.

115
00:06:26,832 --> 00:06:30,335
Think about what the other party truly needs.

116
00:06:32,256 --> 00:06:35,556
Mr. Ishikura's term as GM ends this year.

117
00:06:36,176 --> 00:06:40,543
The Vikings lost five players
due to the drug investigation.

118
00:06:40,543 --> 00:06:42,334
Five players.

119
00:06:42,334 --> 00:06:45,125
If he doesn't show results in this adversity,

120
00:06:45,125 --> 00:06:47,994
Mr. Ishikura won't be reappointed as GM.

121
00:06:49,400 --> 00:06:53,629
What he needs now,
are players who can show immediate results.

122
00:06:54,401 --> 00:06:59,206
You don't understand Mr. Ishikura at all.

123
00:06:59,206 --> 00:07:01,916
The one who doesn't understand
Mr. Ishikura...

124
00:07:03,404 --> 00:07:05,120
Is you.

125
00:07:12,414 --> 00:07:16,295
It's true my term ends this year.

126
00:07:17,046 --> 00:07:20,127
I'd much rather go out on a good note.

127
00:07:21,156 --> 00:07:25,670
Which is why I've given up on winning.

128
00:07:25,670 --> 00:07:27,059
What?

129
00:07:27,059 --> 00:07:31,125
I'll secure promising young players,

130
00:07:31,125 --> 00:07:33,364
and have the Vikings win in two years.

131
00:07:34,488 --> 00:07:36,576
That's what's best for the team.

132
00:07:38,401 --> 00:07:40,469
GM Sakurazaki.

133
00:07:43,736 --> 00:07:45,852
Take Tatsuya Kudo with you.

134
00:07:47,201 --> 00:07:51,381
But, Mr. Ishikura.
Don't you want to be reappointed?

135
00:07:51,381 --> 00:07:54,172
Do you know of his background?

136
00:07:55,139 --> 00:07:57,324
Mr. Ishikura was appointed GM in 2019,

137
00:07:57,324 --> 00:08:00,844
when the Vikings' performance
began to decline.

138
00:08:01,849 --> 00:08:05,364
He started by letting go
of a veteran slugger,

139
00:08:05,364 --> 00:08:07,886
and shifted his focus
to developing young players.

140
00:08:07,886 --> 00:08:12,511
Naturally, there was a lot of criticism
from fans and players alike.

141
00:08:13,037 --> 00:08:17,702
Yet the Vikings became a pitching powerhouse,

142
00:08:17,702 --> 00:08:21,869
and won two consecutive series from 2021.

143
00:08:21,869 --> 00:08:26,155
Enough about me.
I'm considered a disgrace nowadays.

144
00:08:27,636 --> 00:08:32,631
He doesn't care about immediate return,
or his own reputation.

145
00:08:32,631 --> 00:08:35,802
He prioritizes the future of the team
above all else.

146
00:08:38,545 --> 00:08:43,593
As it stands,
you could never understand Mr. Ishikura.

147
00:08:48,828 --> 00:08:50,692
If you'll excuse me.

148
00:09:15,417 --> 00:09:17,493
Really get into it, yeah? You're at bat.

149
00:09:50,026 --> 00:09:51,602
Whoa!

150
00:10:00,263 --> 00:10:05,739
♪ <i>Overflowing power,
surging fighting spirit!</i> ♪

151
00:10:05,739 --> 00:10:11,181
♪ <i>Carry our dreams, upon that arch!</i> ♪

152
00:10:11,181 --> 00:10:14,083
Hit it out of the park, Kudo!

153
00:10:14,083 --> 00:10:17,804
Kudo! Kudo!

154
00:10:17,804 --> 00:10:20,181
Welcome back!

155
00:10:20,181 --> 00:10:21,966
Quit messing around!

156
00:10:23,357 --> 00:10:26,174
You'd better watch yourselves later.

157
00:10:26,174 --> 00:10:28,049
Come on, it was just a prank!

158
00:10:28,049 --> 00:10:30,321
I'm not having it. Apologize.

159
00:10:30,321 --> 00:10:32,935
Bow down, and say you're sorry!

160
00:10:34,663 --> 00:10:35,923
- Like this?
- Yeah.

161
00:10:35,923 --> 00:10:37,974
Moo!

162
00:10:41,797 --> 00:10:44,616
What? He's the one in the wrong!

163
00:10:44,616 --> 00:10:46,969
He was messing around!

164
00:10:48,157 --> 00:10:50,595
I knew it stank in here.

165
00:10:50,595 --> 00:10:52,740
How'd a Viking sneak his way inside?

166
00:10:52,740 --> 00:10:54,695
- Yeah!
- Boo!

167
00:10:54,695 --> 00:10:56,601
You're not making any sense, Kijima.

168
00:10:56,601 --> 00:11:00,581
I always have, and always will be a Dreamer!

169
00:11:00,581 --> 00:11:02,153
Big talk.

170
00:11:02,153 --> 00:11:03,941
Get him!

171
00:11:08,820 --> 00:11:11,806
Put me down! Put me down!

172
00:11:12,832 --> 00:11:14,944
You'd better watch your backs later!

173
00:11:42,840 --> 00:11:44,917
We did it!

174
00:11:44,917 --> 00:11:47,626
Come on, smile!

175
00:11:47,626 --> 00:11:50,310
Forcing another smile on me, I see.

176
00:11:50,310 --> 00:11:51,541
I think I'll pass.

177
00:11:51,541 --> 00:11:54,077
You could learn to loosen up a little.

178
00:11:54,077 --> 00:11:56,883
Don't you know how important it is to smile?

179
00:11:56,883 --> 00:11:59,396
It's far too early to celebrate.

180
00:11:59,396 --> 00:12:01,919
We know President Negishi
will pull another scheme

181
00:12:01,919 --> 00:12:05,825
using Kudo's high salary as an excuse.

182
00:12:07,814 --> 00:12:08,840
Come in.

183
00:12:08,840 --> 00:12:10,809
Excuse me.

184
00:12:10,809 --> 00:12:12,752
What's wrong?

185
00:12:12,752 --> 00:12:15,165
We need money, right?

186
00:12:15,165 --> 00:12:17,765
I gathered us advertising contracts.

187
00:12:18,400 --> 00:12:19,801
What?

188
00:12:26,425 --> 00:12:28,540
[Requested amount: 5 million yen]

189
00:12:28,540 --> 00:12:30,147
You did all this by yourself?

190
00:12:30,147 --> 00:12:31,763
That's amazing!

191
00:12:31,763 --> 00:12:33,890
I tried giving it a go.

192
00:12:34,841 --> 00:12:36,040
What suddenly motivated you?

193
00:12:36,040 --> 00:12:38,468
That has to be Kudo's return.

194
00:12:38,468 --> 00:12:39,486
That's right.

195
00:12:40,455 --> 00:12:43,449
Hiromi is Tatsuya Kudo's mother.

196
00:12:46,160 --> 00:12:48,980
Gosh, it's just a nickname!

197
00:12:48,980 --> 00:12:52,885
The Kudo Burger, his cheer song,
his baseball classes...

198
00:12:52,885 --> 00:12:56,263
Even Kudo's official social media account
was Hiromi's idea.

199
00:12:56,263 --> 00:13:00,268
I believe the current culture of our team
was created by Hiromi.

200
00:13:00,268 --> 00:13:03,116
Oh, please! You're flattering me!

201
00:13:03,116 --> 00:13:05,907
If you're that capable,
you could have told me sooner.

202
00:13:05,907 --> 00:13:09,854
That remark is exactly why I didn't bother!

203
00:13:10,591 --> 00:13:14,030
Of course, I used to have passion.

204
00:13:14,030 --> 00:13:17,357
I wanted to achieve results
and be recognized.

205
00:13:17,357 --> 00:13:20,633
With how capable you are,
certainly you received recognition.

206
00:13:20,633 --> 00:13:25,667
Yes. Before I knew it,
I was promoted to Director.

207
00:13:25,667 --> 00:13:30,041
But with work forced onto me,
I lost all time for my personal life.

208
00:13:30,041 --> 00:13:32,798
That's why I quit working hard.

209
00:13:34,977 --> 00:13:37,608
But I enjoyed myself this time around.

210
00:13:37,608 --> 00:13:40,887
It's not bad to try once in a while.

211
00:13:40,887 --> 00:13:44,711
Oh! That's right!
I have to visit 30 places today!

212
00:13:44,711 --> 00:13:47,119
Oh, no! I won't make it!

213
00:13:47,119 --> 00:13:49,346
If you'll excuse me!

214
00:13:53,489 --> 00:13:56,330
We've become a team that can aim for victory.

215
00:13:58,183 --> 00:13:59,858
The players.

216
00:14:01,331 --> 00:14:02,995
Administration.

217
00:14:04,089 --> 00:14:06,135
Everyone is looking ahead.

218
00:14:09,862 --> 00:14:12,123
Except for one individual.

219
00:14:13,830 --> 00:14:15,684
Excuse me.

220
00:14:18,759 --> 00:14:21,856
- Did you call for me?
- You know why I called.

221
00:14:23,132 --> 00:14:24,642
What do I look like to you?

222
00:14:26,745 --> 00:14:30,430
Can't even guess how I feel?

223
00:14:30,430 --> 00:14:34,228
I'm angry.

224
00:14:35,423 --> 00:14:37,519
Very angry.

225
00:14:37,519 --> 00:14:38,967
Yes, sir.

226
00:14:38,967 --> 00:14:42,215
Your schemes are going nowhere.

227
00:14:42,215 --> 00:14:46,582
Question! Can you run a business
on mere fantasies?

228
00:14:46,582 --> 00:14:49,334
Well? Can you?

229
00:14:49,334 --> 00:14:51,184
No, sir. My humblest apologies.

230
00:14:51,184 --> 00:14:54,557
Is apologizing your only talent?

231
00:14:54,557 --> 00:14:56,822
Thanks to that entire drug ordeal,

232
00:14:56,822 --> 00:15:00,746
every team owner holds a grudge against us.

233
00:15:00,746 --> 00:15:02,502
Sir, I...

234
00:15:02,502 --> 00:15:03,797
I will deal with it appropriately.

235
00:15:03,797 --> 00:15:05,422
Shut up! Shut up!

236
00:15:05,422 --> 00:15:07,409
I'm sick of hearing it!

237
00:15:10,911 --> 00:15:15,590
I thought you were nothing like your father.

238
00:15:15,590 --> 00:15:18,113
I entrusted you with managing that team.

239
00:15:18,113 --> 00:15:21,175
Do you know how he handled that task?

240
00:15:21,175 --> 00:15:24,350
He changed light bulbs!

241
00:15:24,350 --> 00:15:28,089
His subordinates trampled all over him!

242
00:15:28,089 --> 00:15:30,035
What is wrong with that man?

243
00:15:30,035 --> 00:15:32,541
He's truly a miserable sight.

244
00:15:36,648 --> 00:15:38,591
That was my one mistake.

245
00:15:38,591 --> 00:15:42,543
I entrusted the team to an incompetent man.

246
00:15:42,543 --> 00:15:48,396
Thanks to him, the mighty Yaoshima Group
had been branded as an utterly failure!

247
00:15:48,396 --> 00:15:49,545
I am different.

248
00:15:49,545 --> 00:15:50,924
Huh?

249
00:15:51,655 --> 00:15:55,382
I will vow to disband that team!

250
00:16:04,104 --> 00:16:07,169
Will you pin the blame on that GM?

251
00:16:07,730 --> 00:16:10,005
On this man here?

252
00:16:12,750 --> 00:16:16,992
Is this man competent?

253
00:16:18,556 --> 00:16:21,525
Well? Is he?

254
00:16:23,793 --> 00:16:27,331
He is competent, in a way.

255
00:16:30,910 --> 00:16:32,876
Use him if he's useful.

256
00:16:32,876 --> 00:16:34,397
That's all.

257
00:16:36,557 --> 00:16:38,083
Yes, sir.

258
00:16:45,884 --> 00:16:48,649
Here, drink up.

259
00:16:48,649 --> 00:16:50,754
Please state your business.

260
00:16:51,928 --> 00:16:54,224
Now, now, don't be so hasty.

261
00:16:54,224 --> 00:16:55,571
Drink.

262
00:16:56,687 --> 00:16:58,337
No, thank you.

263
00:17:07,135 --> 00:17:12,656
You could never understand
the struggles I've endured.

264
00:17:16,236 --> 00:17:21,538
I heard you made another trade
without my permission.

265
00:17:21,538 --> 00:17:24,907
Worry not, we've already negotiated salaries.

266
00:17:24,907 --> 00:17:27,582
Enough flaunting how capable you are.

267
00:17:27,582 --> 00:17:31,119
Does basic courtesy evade you as a concept?

268
00:17:36,778 --> 00:17:39,359
Today, I signed a deal

269
00:17:39,359 --> 00:17:45,798
to build a hotel worth 30 billion yen.

270
00:17:47,083 --> 00:17:51,420
To celebrate trading a player
for a mere 100 million yen?

271
00:17:51,420 --> 00:17:54,983
How utterly ridiculous.

272
00:17:54,983 --> 00:17:59,820
The president of a baseball team,
building a hotel.

273
00:17:59,820 --> 00:18:02,149
I never held any interest in baseball.

274
00:18:02,149 --> 00:18:04,944
My priorities lie in bigger places.

275
00:18:04,944 --> 00:18:08,933
Unlike you.

276
00:18:12,562 --> 00:18:14,896
Do you know anything about baseball?

277
00:18:15,693 --> 00:18:17,007
Huh?

278
00:18:17,007 --> 00:18:20,912
"Some people are born on third base,
and think they hit a triple".

279
00:18:23,004 --> 00:18:24,732
What are you getting at?

280
00:18:26,084 --> 00:18:28,411
A person like you, blessed with good fortune,

281
00:18:28,411 --> 00:18:34,269
will know nothing of our struggle
to hit that triple.

282
00:18:38,755 --> 00:18:40,372
If you'll excuse me.

283
00:18:46,833 --> 00:18:49,989
I brought you some good news, you know.

284
00:18:52,667 --> 00:18:56,905
I thought you and I had something in common.

285
00:18:57,473 --> 00:19:01,734
No, I might have even believed it.

286
00:19:04,956 --> 00:19:07,172
But it seems it was a misunderstanding.

287
00:19:30,749 --> 00:19:33,509
The trade is officially complete.

288
00:19:34,223 --> 00:19:36,509
That's good to hear.

289
00:19:36,509 --> 00:19:39,580
Please expect great things from us
this season.

290
00:19:41,143 --> 00:19:44,452
I only ask that
you receive your victor's bonus

291
00:19:44,452 --> 00:19:47,422
as listed in your contract.

292
00:19:49,908 --> 00:19:52,728
Would you permit me one question?

293
00:19:53,525 --> 00:19:57,562
I was only known as an incompetent manager.

294
00:19:57,562 --> 00:19:59,627
Why did you re-sign me,
despite my reputation?

295
00:20:00,729 --> 00:20:02,381
Mr. Nishida.

296
00:20:03,982 --> 00:20:06,174
I never once thought you were incompetent.

297
00:20:07,634 --> 00:20:09,128
Why is that?

298
00:20:10,711 --> 00:20:16,069
You seem to get along with Sakurazaki.

299
00:20:16,069 --> 00:20:18,546
I've never met anyone like him.

300
00:20:18,546 --> 00:20:21,131
He's serious about about winning the series.

301
00:20:22,756 --> 00:20:25,000
He's just a fool.

302
00:20:25,980 --> 00:20:28,613
Sir, why not cooperate with the GM?

303
00:20:31,567 --> 00:20:35,896
If you take his side, you're fired.

304
00:20:43,187 --> 00:20:48,828
You have something you must protect, no?

305
00:21:08,762 --> 00:21:12,705
Why did you ask Mr. Nishida to stay on?

306
00:21:12,705 --> 00:21:14,711
Would you rather he quit?

307
00:21:14,711 --> 00:21:16,804
No, that's not what I meant.

308
00:21:16,804 --> 00:21:19,098
You've made so many other reforms.

309
00:21:19,098 --> 00:21:22,628
What convinced you to keep our manager?

310
00:21:22,628 --> 00:21:26,076
April 16th, 2016.

311
00:21:26,076 --> 00:21:28,484
The Dreams were up against the Sabres.

312
00:21:28,484 --> 00:21:30,325
Do you remember the game?

313
00:21:31,595 --> 00:21:33,188
No...

314
00:21:33,188 --> 00:21:39,373
At the time, Sawada was no star.
He was still a rookie on-the-rise.

315
00:21:40,752 --> 00:21:42,583
Towards the end of the game,

316
00:21:42,583 --> 00:21:47,001
Sawada was clearly at his limit.

317
00:21:47,001 --> 00:21:51,512
But Mr. Nishida kept Sawada pitching.

318
00:21:51,512 --> 00:21:56,248
Right. Oyama hit a homer
in the ninth inning. We lost that game.

319
00:21:57,349 --> 00:21:59,537
Sure, he may have given up a home run.

320
00:22:00,925 --> 00:22:03,374
But it was a genius move
on Mr. Nishida's part.

321
00:22:04,526 --> 00:22:08,279
Shouldn't he have swapped our pitchers?

322
00:22:09,748 --> 00:22:11,858
Though the Dreams lost that game,

323
00:22:12,460 --> 00:22:16,155
Takeru Sawada made a name for himself.

324
00:22:16,155 --> 00:22:18,547
Fans remembered his indomitable spirit.

325
00:22:20,460 --> 00:22:22,747
He etched himself into their hearts.

326
00:22:23,947 --> 00:22:29,505
It was undoubtedly Mr. Nishida
who made him a star.

327
00:22:31,667 --> 00:22:34,520
So that's how you saw the Manager.

328
00:22:35,139 --> 00:22:37,554
Mr. Nishida's presence here...

329
00:22:39,806 --> 00:22:42,214
was what gave me hope in the Dreams.

330
00:22:43,074 --> 00:22:46,536
I wish you led with that.

331
00:22:46,536 --> 00:22:47,952
Bad news, bad news!

332
00:22:47,952 --> 00:22:49,063
- Watch out!
- Woah!

333
00:22:49,063 --> 00:22:50,602
Coming through!

334
00:22:50,602 --> 00:22:52,671
Sorry! GM, Prez!

335
00:22:52,671 --> 00:22:55,335
Bad news! Sawada, he...

336
00:22:56,221 --> 00:22:58,197
He's been traded away.

337
00:23:00,830 --> 00:23:02,202
Who approved it?

338
00:23:02,202 --> 00:23:05,639
President Negishi and the Manager.

339
00:23:18,444 --> 00:23:21,696
The GM is responsible
for strengthening the team

340
00:23:21,696 --> 00:23:24,652
during the Stove League.

341
00:23:24,652 --> 00:23:28,190
And you, the Manager,

342
00:23:28,190 --> 00:23:32,957
are responsible for igniting
the hearts of our fans.

343
00:23:39,252 --> 00:23:41,307
[Aim for the top spot in Japan!]

344
00:23:41,307 --> 00:23:45,747
[We love you, Manager Nishida!]

345
00:24:06,282 --> 00:24:11,621
What's wrong? You look utterly terrifying.

346
00:24:11,621 --> 00:24:14,672
I'd advise you against squinting so long.

347
00:24:14,672 --> 00:24:16,760
You're going to need glasses.

348
00:24:16,760 --> 00:24:18,260
Don't be ridiculous.

349
00:24:21,329 --> 00:24:23,265
I know that look.

350
00:24:24,789 --> 00:24:27,620
You seem to be against Sawada's trade.

351
00:24:27,620 --> 00:24:29,251
Damn you!

352
00:24:29,792 --> 00:24:32,415
How much of a scumbag are you?

353
00:24:32,415 --> 00:24:34,124
Well, well.

354
00:24:34,794 --> 00:24:38,130
Have you forgotten your manners?

355
00:24:38,130 --> 00:24:42,051
You don't understand how to run a team.

356
00:24:42,051 --> 00:24:43,955
You should look to the future.

357
00:24:43,955 --> 00:24:46,788
Like you have any right
harping about the future.

358
00:24:49,938 --> 00:24:56,158
The reason we discussed this without you
is simple.

359
00:24:58,399 --> 00:25:00,889
You and I cannot see eye to eye.

360
00:25:03,949 --> 00:25:07,355
You traded Sawada for two low-performing,
minor league players.

361
00:25:07,355 --> 00:25:10,253
What did we gain from that exchange?

362
00:25:10,784 --> 00:25:13,228
You misunderstand.

363
00:25:13,228 --> 00:25:19,334
I saw potential in their swings.

364
00:25:20,416 --> 00:25:22,220
He's a pitcher.

365
00:25:22,823 --> 00:25:27,219
One of them is a pitcher, not a fielder!

366
00:25:27,219 --> 00:25:34,038
Then I saw potential
in their swings, and pitches.

367
00:25:34,038 --> 00:25:36,438
Is that what you're going to tell the fans?

368
00:25:37,054 --> 00:25:41,968
No, no. I'll have the manager deal with them.

369
00:25:41,968 --> 00:25:45,880
I'm sure he'll figure something out.

370
00:25:47,963 --> 00:25:50,161
The manager was a talented individual

371
00:25:50,161 --> 00:25:55,716
you signed on for three more years, yes?

372
00:25:57,567 --> 00:26:03,091
Now, it's time for your rebuttal.

373
00:26:11,946 --> 00:26:15,292
Oh, my. Don't have one?

374
00:26:16,040 --> 00:26:21,113
What happened to talking back, hm?

375
00:26:34,764 --> 00:26:36,303
You're the ace.

376
00:26:36,303 --> 00:26:39,401
They can't trade you away for minor leaguers.

377
00:26:42,524 --> 00:26:46,933
Players can't choose their teams.
I just got unlucky, that's all.

378
00:26:49,437 --> 00:26:51,853
Was this the GM's decision?

379
00:26:51,853 --> 00:26:53,164
Of course not.

380
00:26:53,164 --> 00:26:55,011
Then who approved the trade?

381
00:26:57,661 --> 00:26:59,005
I'm fine, seriously.

382
00:26:59,005 --> 00:27:02,196
Just focus on hitting those homers.

383
00:27:08,872 --> 00:27:11,708
Did you really agree to this trade?

384
00:27:12,593 --> 00:27:16,610
It is my right as manager
to decide who's on the team.

385
00:27:16,610 --> 00:27:18,322
I don't understand!

386
00:27:18,322 --> 00:27:21,349
I thought we had potential
to win the series this year!

387
00:27:22,560 --> 00:27:24,380
That's right.

388
00:27:24,380 --> 00:27:27,681
Didn't you feel it
when we had our practice game?

389
00:27:27,681 --> 00:27:33,231
The GM is also responsible for
re-signing an incompetent man like myself.

390
00:27:37,234 --> 00:27:39,585
Is that how you really feel?

391
00:27:42,568 --> 00:27:45,441
Do you realize how much he...

392
00:27:51,161 --> 00:27:52,748
I am truly...

393
00:27:53,475 --> 00:27:55,787
Truly, disappointed.

394
00:27:55,787 --> 00:27:57,587
I should have known you were...

395
00:28:04,123 --> 00:28:05,718
Excuse me.

396
00:28:32,623 --> 00:28:35,435
No, thanks. If I drink coffee now,
I won't sleep.

397
00:28:35,435 --> 00:28:38,028
You weren't planning on sleeping anyway.

398
00:28:39,759 --> 00:28:42,654
Don't get so cocky.

399
00:28:47,438 --> 00:28:49,122
Whoa! Gosh!

400
00:28:49,122 --> 00:28:50,633
Bitter!

401
00:28:50,633 --> 00:28:52,166
I'm sorry.

402
00:28:52,166 --> 00:28:53,131
Don't hit me.

403
00:28:53,131 --> 00:28:56,552
I won't hit you over a cup of coffee,
you scaredy-cat.

404
00:28:56,552 --> 00:28:58,108
Sorry.

405
00:28:59,408 --> 00:29:01,296
Okay, wow.

406
00:29:01,296 --> 00:29:03,238
That's bitter.

407
00:29:03,238 --> 00:29:04,795
These were from a high-end store!

408
00:29:04,795 --> 00:29:08,944
What a serious rip-off. I can't believe it.

409
00:29:08,944 --> 00:29:12,466
They're always preaching "customer first",

410
00:29:12,466 --> 00:29:14,972
but it's all just a business strategy.

411
00:29:14,972 --> 00:29:17,258
I really hate businessmen.

412
00:29:17,258 --> 00:29:19,398
They only care about making a profit.

413
00:29:19,398 --> 00:29:21,761
I'm never buying from this shop again.

414
00:29:21,761 --> 00:29:24,377
- Should I tweet about it?
- Miyahara!

415
00:29:24,377 --> 00:29:26,424
What about President Negishi?

416
00:29:27,192 --> 00:29:28,170
Huh?

417
00:29:28,170 --> 00:29:31,422
A businessman never does anything
to lose money, right?

418
00:29:31,422 --> 00:29:32,857
Yes?

419
00:29:34,098 --> 00:29:36,042
Huh? Wait a minute.

420
00:29:36,042 --> 00:29:39,077
Where are you going? Hey! Wait!

421
00:29:43,944 --> 00:29:45,662
Sorry for calling you out at this hour.

422
00:29:46,349 --> 00:29:47,932
What did you need?

423
00:29:49,164 --> 00:29:52,277
What do you think
was the purpose of this trade?

424
00:29:55,199 --> 00:29:59,088
Only the Titans benefit from it.

425
00:29:59,088 --> 00:30:00,885
Isn't that strange?

426
00:30:02,177 --> 00:30:05,683
President Negishi is renowned
as a competent businessman.

427
00:30:05,683 --> 00:30:08,602
A businessman wouldn't make a losing trade.

428
00:30:08,602 --> 00:30:12,900
Even so, the trade has already been decided.

429
00:30:16,900 --> 00:30:19,062
There's nothing more we can do.

430
00:30:27,148 --> 00:30:29,965
Please don't be so hard on yourself.

431
00:30:34,246 --> 00:30:36,610
Share the burden with us.

432
00:30:43,536 --> 00:30:45,885
Let's think about how to protect the Dreams.

433
00:30:47,067 --> 00:30:49,104
Together.

434
00:30:54,855 --> 00:30:57,401
Min Jong turned down the Korean draft...

435
00:30:58,135 --> 00:31:01,233
to challenge himself here, in Japan.

436
00:31:05,948 --> 00:31:07,781
Kudo turned over a new leaf,

437
00:31:09,229 --> 00:31:11,706
and is now a man reborn.

438
00:31:14,851 --> 00:31:18,608
Iwata bets on this season,
despite his injury.

439
00:31:22,890 --> 00:31:26,521
Kijima pitches,
knowing this year could be his last.

440
00:31:31,418 --> 00:31:35,888
We still have many players
we need to protect.

441
00:31:37,976 --> 00:31:40,352
Without Sawada's pitching,

442
00:31:41,983 --> 00:31:44,176
the team has no chance at victory.

443
00:31:45,320 --> 00:31:46,715
What if...

444
00:31:47,589 --> 00:31:49,951
Even if we can't win the series...

445
00:31:52,413 --> 00:31:55,682
We can aim to become a team
that doesn't go down without a fight.

446
00:31:56,937 --> 00:32:01,357
A team that aims to be victorious,
despite its losses!

447
00:32:05,497 --> 00:32:07,654
Not everything is about winning.

448
00:32:09,429 --> 00:32:12,192
We can learn something important from loss.

449
00:32:12,192 --> 00:32:14,228
If we can't win the series...

450
00:32:19,816 --> 00:32:22,152
then my role as GM has no meaning.

451
00:32:22,948 --> 00:32:26,005
The reason I trust you...

452
00:32:27,063 --> 00:32:29,599
isn't because of your wins.

453
00:32:33,154 --> 00:32:36,507
It's because of your unwavering resolve.

454
00:32:38,126 --> 00:32:43,606
And that resolve of yours motivates us all.

455
00:32:50,444 --> 00:32:52,140
Sorry I bothered at a late hour.

456
00:32:53,302 --> 00:32:54,876
Good night.

457
00:33:04,695 --> 00:33:06,709
Protect the Dreams!

458
00:33:06,709 --> 00:33:08,290
Protect them!

459
00:33:08,290 --> 00:33:11,679
GM Sakurazaki,
take responsibility for the trade!

460
00:33:11,679 --> 00:33:13,629
Take responsibility!

461
00:33:13,629 --> 00:33:16,864
Withdraw the trade of Takeru Sawada!

462
00:33:16,864 --> 00:33:18,716
Withdraw it!

463
00:33:18,716 --> 00:33:20,487
Give us back Sawada!

464
00:33:20,487 --> 00:33:22,844
Give us back Sawada!

465
00:33:22,844 --> 00:33:25,099
Resign, incompetent GM!

466
00:33:25,099 --> 00:33:27,267
Resign!

467
00:33:31,265 --> 00:33:34,249
Don't they have jobs?

468
00:33:34,249 --> 00:33:38,504
Some people have weekdays off.
It's also possible they're taking paid leave.

469
00:33:38,504 --> 00:33:40,936
Paid leave, to protest?

470
00:33:40,936 --> 00:33:43,973
That's how strongly they feel about the team.

471
00:33:43,973 --> 00:33:47,539
Isn't baseball just a hobby?

472
00:33:47,539 --> 00:33:49,004
Huh?

473
00:33:49,004 --> 00:33:51,563
It's just a game.

474
00:33:52,554 --> 00:33:54,954
Honestly.

475
00:33:54,954 --> 00:33:57,923
They're wasting their precious working hours.

476
00:33:57,923 --> 00:33:59,986
President Negishi, with all due respect...

477
00:34:01,188 --> 00:34:04,180
Some people dedicate their lives
to their hobbies.

478
00:34:07,206 --> 00:34:12,334
How utterly ridiculous.

479
00:34:16,557 --> 00:34:22,937
[President of Baseball Operations]
[Enjoy your day off.]

480
00:34:26,205 --> 00:34:28,094
You saved a number?

481
00:34:29,325 --> 00:34:31,835
I needed it for work.

482
00:34:31,835 --> 00:34:33,711
That's unusual.

483
00:34:36,864 --> 00:34:40,882
But I'm glad.
You finally found yourself some friends.

484
00:34:42,411 --> 00:34:44,653
Friends?

485
00:34:44,653 --> 00:34:46,894
- It's not like that.
- Really?

486
00:34:47,837 --> 00:34:52,923
Surely you share your joys
and sorrows with them.

487
00:34:58,704 --> 00:35:00,476
So, is there anyone new in your life?

488
00:35:03,745 --> 00:35:05,429
Of course not.

489
00:35:05,429 --> 00:35:07,183
Why not?

490
00:35:07,717 --> 00:35:10,978
- It's not necessary.
- Who decided that?

491
00:35:16,571 --> 00:35:20,937
You get to decide, and break those rules.

492
00:35:29,081 --> 00:35:30,223
Speaking of which,

493
00:35:30,223 --> 00:35:34,073
is it true the Yaoshima Group
is defunding its supermarkets?

494
00:35:34,768 --> 00:35:39,833
If so, what then?
I'd hate for my local chain to disappear.

495
00:35:39,833 --> 00:35:42,412
I still can't accept that trade!

496
00:35:42,412 --> 00:35:44,380
Is President Negishi abandoning the team?

497
00:35:44,380 --> 00:35:47,025
No, he wouldn't actually disband us.

498
00:35:47,025 --> 00:35:50,779
But he's the one dragging us down.

499
00:35:50,779 --> 00:35:54,324
What a grim tale.

500
00:35:54,324 --> 00:35:55,797
I want to hear none of it.

501
00:35:55,797 --> 00:35:58,117
Didn't he tell you anything?

502
00:35:58,117 --> 00:36:00,077
No, I didn't...

503
00:36:00,077 --> 00:36:01,885
But you practically cling to him.

504
00:36:01,885 --> 00:36:03,316
I don't cling to him.

505
00:36:03,316 --> 00:36:04,891
I'm just a close aide.

506
00:36:04,891 --> 00:36:06,207
Say what?

507
00:36:06,207 --> 00:36:08,689
- You bootlicker!
- What did I do?

508
00:36:08,689 --> 00:36:10,842
Or what? Is it my turn to be blamed now?

509
00:36:10,842 --> 00:36:13,389
Of course it's your turn!

510
00:36:13,389 --> 00:36:16,371
You're always hyping up the president,

511
00:36:16,371 --> 00:36:18,538
happily agreeing to whatever he says!

512
00:36:18,538 --> 00:36:20,292
- You bootlicker!
- Bootlicker!

513
00:36:20,292 --> 00:36:22,705
You're the last person
who should be criticizing me!

514
00:36:22,705 --> 00:36:26,098
That's true.
Is it because our team is in deficit?

515
00:36:26,098 --> 00:36:28,919
That's a real possibility.

516
00:36:28,919 --> 00:36:32,887
But if we win the series this year,
can't we make back our deficit?

517
00:36:32,887 --> 00:36:34,472
President Negishi doesn't think so!

518
00:36:34,472 --> 00:36:37,751
Rumors have been circulating for a while now.

519
00:36:37,751 --> 00:36:40,723
Maybe President Negishi
really is looking for team buyers.

520
00:36:40,723 --> 00:36:43,058
I wonder what's going to happen to us...

521
00:36:43,058 --> 00:36:43,864
Ouch!

522
00:36:43,864 --> 00:36:47,255
Don't worry about yourself!
Worry about the team!

523
00:36:47,255 --> 00:36:50,215
I wonder if I'll stop getting hit, too.

524
00:36:50,215 --> 00:36:53,342
The players and coaches only know baseball.

525
00:36:53,342 --> 00:36:57,217
We have to be the ones
to stop our owner's tyranny.

526
00:36:57,217 --> 00:37:00,146
For now, let's do what we can.

527
00:37:02,512 --> 00:37:04,558
But what can we do?

528
00:37:06,959 --> 00:37:08,708
Morning.

529
00:37:08,708 --> 00:37:09,743
Good morning!

530
00:37:09,743 --> 00:37:12,099
Everyone, listen up!

531
00:37:12,901 --> 00:37:17,488
To protest management,
the two of us will be boycotting practice.

532
00:37:23,092 --> 00:37:26,697
But hey, don't feel forced to join us.

533
00:37:27,314 --> 00:37:32,529
Listen up. Kijima and I
will be boycotting practice!

534
00:37:32,529 --> 00:37:34,023
No one's forced to join us!

535
00:37:34,023 --> 00:37:36,104
- Understand?
- Yes, sir!

536
00:37:36,104 --> 00:37:38,464
Kudo, why did you repeat our statement?

537
00:37:38,464 --> 00:37:39,426
Huh?

538
00:37:39,426 --> 00:37:41,255
It totally sounds like
you're pressuring them.

539
00:37:41,255 --> 00:37:43,269
- Really?
- Yeah.

540
00:37:43,975 --> 00:37:45,542
No pressure!

541
00:37:45,542 --> 00:37:47,700
- Understand?
- Yes, sir!

542
00:37:47,700 --> 00:37:50,360
- See?
- Don't 'see?' me!

543
00:37:56,482 --> 00:37:58,636
Manager Nishida.

544
00:37:58,636 --> 00:38:01,327
Is it true you agreed to the trade?

545
00:38:02,977 --> 00:38:05,294
Say something!

546
00:38:05,954 --> 00:38:07,413
But why?

547
00:38:07,413 --> 00:38:11,387
Are you getting money from President Negishi?

548
00:38:13,858 --> 00:38:16,115
At least give us one excuse!

549
00:38:16,115 --> 00:38:19,117
Other teams are finalizing their lineups.

550
00:38:19,117 --> 00:38:20,952
Don't just ignore us!

551
00:38:20,952 --> 00:38:23,090
Manager Nishida.

552
00:38:23,090 --> 00:38:24,770
Nishida!

553
00:38:25,806 --> 00:38:29,711
I know! I'll work extra hard,
and get us Sawada back!

554
00:38:29,711 --> 00:38:32,056
That'd just make the owner happy.

555
00:38:32,056 --> 00:38:35,238
Darn! What should we do?

556
00:38:36,125 --> 00:38:41,277
Can't you find a way to get through
to the president, Director Bootlicker?

557
00:38:41,277 --> 00:38:44,344
Hey, I don't appreciate the nicknames!

558
00:38:44,344 --> 00:38:47,025
Besides, my words mean nothing to him.

559
00:38:47,025 --> 00:38:50,007
Then why are you always clinging to him?

560
00:38:50,007 --> 00:38:52,295
- Seriously!
- Say what? You pipsqueak traitor!

561
00:38:52,295 --> 00:38:54,236
What? Who are you calling pipsqueak!

562
00:38:54,236 --> 00:38:55,564
- Huh?
- It's clearly you.

563
00:38:55,564 --> 00:38:57,034
- Oh, really?
- 158 centimeters.

564
00:38:57,034 --> 00:38:58,496
I know! I have an idea!

565
00:38:58,496 --> 00:38:59,417
Denied.

566
00:38:59,417 --> 00:39:01,710
I haven't even said anything yet.

567
00:39:01,710 --> 00:39:03,378
Fine, I'll bite. What is it?

568
00:39:03,378 --> 00:39:04,851
Right.

569
00:39:04,851 --> 00:39:07,618
How about we get the fans on our side?

570
00:39:07,618 --> 00:39:09,120
- The fans?
- Yeah.

571
00:39:09,120 --> 00:39:11,946
Yaoshima's main business is supermarkets.

572
00:39:11,946 --> 00:39:14,464
They wouldn't want
to offend their clientele, right?

573
00:39:14,464 --> 00:39:17,572
Wait. That might be a plausible idea.

574
00:39:17,572 --> 00:39:19,588
See? You should always ask.

575
00:39:19,588 --> 00:39:23,227
But the fans are currently blaming our GM.

576
00:39:23,227 --> 00:39:27,086
To get them on our side,
we'd have to reveal the truth of the trade.

577
00:39:27,086 --> 00:39:31,228
Which means confronting
President Negishi head-on.

578
00:39:37,529 --> 00:39:41,540
Don't look at me like that.

579
00:39:44,665 --> 00:39:47,289
I don't want to be fired.

580
00:39:47,289 --> 00:39:50,182
None of us do.

581
00:39:50,182 --> 00:39:54,765
I have 35 more years of mortgage to pay.

582
00:39:54,765 --> 00:39:58,390
And cat food surprisingly costs a fortune.

583
00:39:58,390 --> 00:40:00,364
- Not to mention insurance.
- Enough, Kikuchi.

584
00:40:00,364 --> 00:40:02,087
How many subscriptions
do you think I have?

585
00:40:02,087 --> 00:40:03,152
Five.

586
00:40:03,152 --> 00:40:04,879
But I...

587
00:40:06,228 --> 00:40:08,935
I've always been a fan of the Dreams.

588
00:40:08,935 --> 00:40:10,411
So...

589
00:40:11,124 --> 00:40:13,815
If it's to protect the Dreams, I'll do it!

590
00:40:13,815 --> 00:40:16,836
I'll leak everything the Yaoshima Group did

591
00:40:16,836 --> 00:40:20,854
to newspapers, journals, you name it!

592
00:40:26,491 --> 00:40:30,261
You lost me there,
could you repeat all that?

593
00:40:30,261 --> 00:40:33,168
Let me have this one moment, please!

594
00:40:33,168 --> 00:40:35,754
I had a feeling
our PR Director would say that.

595
00:40:35,754 --> 00:40:38,716
I've gathered all the incriminating evidence
you'd need.

596
00:40:38,716 --> 00:40:42,285
Seriously? You anticipated my actions?

597
00:40:42,285 --> 00:40:44,378
We believed in you.

598
00:40:45,552 --> 00:40:49,935
This might be the first time
anyone's actually trusted me.

599
00:40:49,935 --> 00:40:52,620
What kind of life have you led?

600
00:40:53,153 --> 00:40:57,463
Though we may not be able to do anything big,

601
00:40:57,463 --> 00:41:03,810
let's show those selfish owners
what we're made of!

602
00:41:03,810 --> 00:41:05,070
Alright!

603
00:41:05,070 --> 00:41:06,576
Let's do this!

604
00:41:06,576 --> 00:41:09,042
Yeah!

605
00:41:09,042 --> 00:41:11,039
Dreams! Dreams!

606
00:41:11,039 --> 00:41:12,975
Dreams! Dreams!

607
00:41:12,975 --> 00:41:14,834
Dreams! Dreams!

608
00:41:14,834 --> 00:41:16,511
Dreams! Dreams!

609
00:41:16,511 --> 00:41:17,922
GM!

610
00:41:17,922 --> 00:41:19,931
Huh? Aren't you off today?

611
00:41:19,931 --> 00:41:21,067
I've rested enough.

612
00:41:21,067 --> 00:41:24,761
That's our GM. Ever the capable man you are!

613
00:41:24,761 --> 00:41:27,196
You're the real bootlicker!

614
00:41:28,948 --> 00:41:31,919
I have something
I'd like to ask your thoughts on.

615
00:41:31,919 --> 00:41:35,846
You're asking for our input? That's rare.

616
00:41:37,940 --> 00:41:39,642
I believe the Dreams...

617
00:41:40,580 --> 00:41:42,688
ought to cut ties with Yaoshima.

618
00:41:42,688 --> 00:41:44,087
What?

619
00:41:45,230 --> 00:41:47,066
If this indeed happens,

620
00:41:47,938 --> 00:41:50,261
I will need all your help.

621
00:42:14,812 --> 00:42:16,363
Excuse me.

622
00:42:20,734 --> 00:42:25,344
Until now, I was unfazed
by whatever enemy came my way.

623
00:42:26,425 --> 00:42:28,998
But when it's someone you trusted,

624
00:42:29,737 --> 00:42:31,510
it takes a toll.

625
00:42:36,934 --> 00:42:41,110
It was for your son... Right?

626
00:42:46,560 --> 00:42:50,579
That desire to sacrifice anything for family.

627
00:42:53,451 --> 00:42:55,751
I know it all too well.

628
00:42:58,129 --> 00:43:05,389
Even so, I didn't want to see the manager
sacrifice his team.

629
00:43:13,127 --> 00:43:15,354
What kind of deal did you make?

630
00:43:18,935 --> 00:43:21,016
I cannot answer that.

631
00:43:27,185 --> 00:43:31,478
Was there a backroom deal?

632
00:43:38,326 --> 00:43:40,388
Then let me rephrase.

633
00:43:41,540 --> 00:43:43,349
Are you alright...

634
00:43:45,713 --> 00:43:46,922
with Sawada retiring?

635
00:43:46,922 --> 00:43:50,927
[Sawada potentially retiring?]
[Minor league trade may be the cause]

636
00:43:50,927 --> 00:43:53,127
Sawada...

637
00:43:53,127 --> 00:43:57,463
You alone can make a difference, Mr. Nishida.

638
00:43:59,093 --> 00:44:01,408
As the Dreams' manager,

639
00:44:02,232 --> 00:44:06,205
you must protect your players.

640
00:44:10,448 --> 00:44:12,950
You don't have just one son.

641
00:44:14,979 --> 00:44:16,882
Don't you think so?

642
00:44:42,142 --> 00:44:46,184
Yaoshima is selling its shopping business,

643
00:44:46,184 --> 00:44:50,691
and pivoting to
corporate-focused medical services.

644
00:44:51,941 --> 00:44:56,013
I wouldn't know a thing about corporations.

645
00:44:57,365 --> 00:45:01,686
Now that Yaoshima doesn't have to worry
about pleasing the public,

646
00:45:01,686 --> 00:45:05,531
they will disband the team immediately.

647
00:45:07,417 --> 00:45:11,451
At this rate, it won't just be Sawada.

648
00:45:11,451 --> 00:45:14,090
All our players will lose their home.

649
00:45:17,873 --> 00:45:20,337
Please give me your contract.

650
00:45:21,400 --> 00:45:25,973
It is our last hope for saving the Dreams.

651
00:45:34,611 --> 00:45:37,270
The Dreams, our stars of the Stove League,

652
00:45:37,270 --> 00:45:39,428
have made an inexplicable trade.

653
00:45:39,428 --> 00:45:42,228
It's truly a flabbergasting decision.

654
00:45:42,228 --> 00:45:43,867
Indeed.

655
00:45:43,867 --> 00:45:48,263
The players suffered a tough winter
after a 30% salary reduction.

656
00:45:48,263 --> 00:45:52,570
Iwata's declaration of a full break
caused quite the stir as well.

657
00:45:52,570 --> 00:45:54,781
And now there are rumors of Sawada retiring?

658
00:45:54,781 --> 00:45:58,420
<i>If Yaoshima doesn't want to run the team,
I wish they'd just quit.</i>

659
00:45:58,420 --> 00:46:00,078
<i>They're harming the entire league.</i>

660
00:46:00,078 --> 00:46:01,246
Not bad!

661
00:46:01,246 --> 00:46:03,032
Huh? Am I being complimented?

662
00:46:03,032 --> 00:46:04,562
I'm so happy!

663
00:46:04,562 --> 00:46:05,838
Are you starving for recognition?

664
00:46:05,838 --> 00:46:07,842
Nice going, Suzumori.

665
00:46:07,842 --> 00:46:08,645
Nice.

666
00:46:08,645 --> 00:46:11,538
Now Yaoshima is under scrutiny.

667
00:46:11,538 --> 00:46:15,008
All that's left is to deliver the final blow.

668
00:46:16,440 --> 00:46:22,347
President Negishi fraudulently sold Sawada
for 200 million yen.

669
00:46:22,347 --> 00:46:23,553
[200 million yen]

670
00:46:23,553 --> 00:46:28,263
So, he made a profit
apart from the official trade.

671
00:46:28,263 --> 00:46:30,174
You were right.

672
00:46:30,901 --> 00:46:32,985
The president was a businessman.

673
00:46:32,985 --> 00:46:36,250
What? Is that a compliment?

674
00:46:36,250 --> 00:46:39,489
Am I being complimented by the GM?

675
00:46:39,489 --> 00:46:41,322
- He complimented me!
- Ow, ow!

676
00:46:41,322 --> 00:46:42,929
Fishing for compliments?

677
00:46:42,929 --> 00:46:45,674
Seeking for approval, perhaps?

678
00:46:45,674 --> 00:46:47,074
- Shut up, Kappa!
- Quiet!

679
00:46:47,074 --> 00:46:50,835
I'll entrust this illicit contract
to the professional committee.

680
00:46:51,541 --> 00:46:55,118
This will be a whistleblower case.

681
00:46:55,118 --> 00:46:58,958
It's not like leaking a story
to a sports talkshow.

682
00:47:00,214 --> 00:47:02,056
What's the worry?

683
00:47:03,184 --> 00:47:06,543
The GM may be fired.

684
00:47:06,543 --> 00:47:08,385
I don't mind.

685
00:47:08,385 --> 00:47:10,855
I do. If you leave us...

686
00:47:10,855 --> 00:47:12,313
It'll be okay.

687
00:47:14,635 --> 00:47:16,420
You all are here.

688
00:47:19,019 --> 00:47:20,867
Even if I am dismissed,

689
00:47:20,867 --> 00:47:22,969
I believe that this team...

690
00:47:23,599 --> 00:47:30,205
will no longer turn a blind eye
to various injustices and issues.

691
00:47:31,931 --> 00:47:36,483
I believe you will face adversity head-on.

692
00:47:39,052 --> 00:47:40,862
Throughout my career,

693
00:47:42,200 --> 00:47:44,590
I have managed to secure several victories.

694
00:47:45,340 --> 00:47:47,926
But I could never protect my teams.

695
00:47:53,272 --> 00:47:54,957
This time for sure.

696
00:47:56,807 --> 00:47:59,316
I hope to protect the team.

697
00:48:08,861 --> 00:48:12,940
These are the details of the backroom deal.

698
00:48:15,197 --> 00:48:19,059
The owner's baffling decision to trade Sawada

699
00:48:19,059 --> 00:48:24,123
left me suspecting foul play.

700
00:48:25,155 --> 00:48:29,985
As seen here,
the Dreams received not only the players,

701
00:48:29,985 --> 00:48:33,730
but an additional 200 million yen in secrecy.

702
00:48:36,817 --> 00:48:43,202
We apologize on the Yaoshima Group's behalf
for their management practices.

703
00:48:43,202 --> 00:48:48,016
The Dreams aim to be a clean team.

704
00:48:48,016 --> 00:48:50,840
Therefore, as GM,

705
00:48:50,840 --> 00:48:57,343
I request the Japanese Baseball Organization
to revoke the trade.

706
00:49:07,297 --> 00:49:09,707
[GM Sakurazaki]

707
00:49:17,000 --> 00:49:18,873
<i>Hello?</i>

708
00:49:18,873 --> 00:49:20,819
Mr. Nishida.

709
00:49:20,819 --> 00:49:23,114
Have you reconsidered?

710
00:49:23,114 --> 00:49:28,510
I made a mistake for selfish reasons.

711
00:49:28,510 --> 00:49:32,831
I don't deserve to lead this team.

712
00:49:33,929 --> 00:49:36,210
You make a valid point.

713
00:49:36,210 --> 00:49:37,627
However...

714
00:49:38,487 --> 00:49:43,125
Though we cannot change the past,
we can change the future.

715
00:49:46,364 --> 00:49:49,965
<i>I'll see you at the stadium.</i>

716
00:50:00,032 --> 00:50:01,587
[200 million was behind the trade]

717
00:50:01,587 --> 00:50:02,647
[Dreams' GM gives us the insider scoop!]

718
00:50:02,647 --> 00:50:05,457
[Yaoshima's the worst]
[Yaoshima are scumbags]

719
00:50:05,457 --> 00:50:06,862
[#BoycottYaoshima]
[#YaoshimaGroup]

720
00:50:06,862 --> 00:50:08,152
[Illicit trade sparks Yaoshima Boycott]

721
00:50:09,854 --> 00:50:13,747
The public is on our side!

722
00:50:15,449 --> 00:50:18,034
- And our fans have started protesting!
- Yes!

723
00:50:18,034 --> 00:50:20,939
We can expect a favorable decision
from the committee.

724
00:50:20,939 --> 00:50:23,745
Let's toast to this! We have to drink!

725
00:50:23,745 --> 00:50:25,146
Alright!

726
00:50:25,146 --> 00:50:26,739
Well said!

727
00:50:26,739 --> 00:50:28,222
Thank you!

728
00:50:28,222 --> 00:50:29,749
Okay, let's chill out.

729
00:50:29,749 --> 00:50:32,200
Everyone's backing away.

730
00:50:32,200 --> 00:50:33,309
No...

731
00:50:33,309 --> 00:50:39,994
The locals must be surprised
to hear of Yaoshima's abuse!

732
00:50:39,994 --> 00:50:41,565
I'm sure, yes.

733
00:50:45,121 --> 00:50:46,429
Huh?

734
00:50:46,429 --> 00:50:47,617
Who's calling?

735
00:50:47,617 --> 00:50:49,364
Oh? Huh?
[Titans President of Baseball Operations]

736
00:50:49,364 --> 00:50:51,319
- Retaliation?
- Protests?

737
00:50:51,319 --> 00:50:52,777
Either way, I'm answering.

738
00:50:52,777 --> 00:50:55,106
Do you really have to?

739
00:50:55,106 --> 00:50:56,524
- Oh...
- Hello.

740
00:50:57,839 --> 00:50:58,959
No.

741
00:51:01,508 --> 00:51:03,247
Well, regarding that...

742
00:51:06,064 --> 00:51:07,932
Yes, you're right.

743
00:51:07,932 --> 00:51:09,261
Yes.

744
00:51:11,403 --> 00:51:12,887
Understood.

745
00:51:12,887 --> 00:51:14,099
Yes.

746
00:51:15,071 --> 00:51:16,785
Thank you.

747
00:51:20,275 --> 00:51:21,907
What did they say?

748
00:51:29,939 --> 00:51:31,633
The Titans...

749
00:51:34,883 --> 00:51:36,513
They have...

750
00:51:44,211 --> 00:51:46,298
They have called off the trade!

751
00:51:48,098 --> 00:51:51,039
Did you have to scare us?

752
00:51:51,039 --> 00:51:52,853
My heart...

753
00:51:52,853 --> 00:51:55,060
It jumped right out my mouth!

754
00:51:55,060 --> 00:51:57,244
Right from my chest!

755
00:51:57,244 --> 00:51:59,310
Hooray!

756
00:52:00,280 --> 00:52:02,004
What do you mean it's off?

757
00:52:02,004 --> 00:52:03,723
No, wait a minute!

758
00:52:08,347 --> 00:52:11,367
[SAWADA]

759
00:52:22,504 --> 00:52:23,961
Hey.

760
00:52:24,924 --> 00:52:28,425
Your teammates were boycotting practice,

761
00:52:28,425 --> 00:52:30,941
and you're throwing pitches?

762
00:52:30,941 --> 00:52:33,195
That's unfair.

763
00:52:34,150 --> 00:52:36,328
It's like you're itching to win.

764
00:52:36,328 --> 00:52:38,300
Welcome back!

765
00:52:40,919 --> 00:52:43,752
Skipping practice is unprofessional.

766
00:52:43,752 --> 00:52:45,396
Touche.

767
00:52:45,396 --> 00:52:46,656
Then let's get practicing.

768
00:52:46,656 --> 00:52:48,468
- Right.
- Shall we?

769
00:52:48,468 --> 00:52:50,585
Practice time.

770
00:52:51,241 --> 00:52:53,598
Psyche! Get him!

771
00:53:11,096 --> 00:53:12,696
Mr. Nishida.

772
00:53:15,178 --> 00:53:18,632
Where are you going?
We finally get to practice.

773
00:53:19,918 --> 00:53:21,593
I'm sorry.

774
00:53:23,618 --> 00:53:26,377
What are you talking about?

775
00:53:26,377 --> 00:53:29,909
Buy us a drink and we're even.

776
00:53:30,578 --> 00:53:32,645
Just act normal, alright?

777
00:53:35,132 --> 00:53:36,315
Like this!

778
00:53:36,315 --> 00:53:39,019
- Don't touch me.
- Disgusting.

779
00:53:39,019 --> 00:53:42,022
Hats on, Manager.

780
00:53:42,022 --> 00:53:43,373
Let's go.

781
00:53:54,302 --> 00:54:01,757
[Trailblazing new Dreams - Dreams 2027]

782
00:54:01,757 --> 00:54:03,477
<i>Onto our next headline.</i>

783
00:54:03,477 --> 00:54:06,300
<i>Yaoshima has sold
a part of its shopping enterprise</i>

784
00:54:06,300 --> 00:54:10,418
<i>to the Kie Trading Co.</i>

785
00:54:10,418 --> 00:54:12,791
<i>The deal included multiple stores,</i>

786
00:54:12,791 --> 00:54:15,903
<i>distribution centers and some real estate.</i>

787
00:54:15,903 --> 00:54:18,977
<i>The transaction is estimated
to be in the billions.</i>

788
00:54:18,977 --> 00:54:20,417
[Ryuta]

789
00:54:20,417 --> 00:54:23,134
<i>Yaoshima will use this as an opportunity</i>

790
00:54:23,134 --> 00:54:25,247
<i>to break away from their niche
of community supermarkets.</i>

791
00:54:25,247 --> 00:54:26,163
Yes?

792
00:54:26,163 --> 00:54:29,646
What're you doing over a meager 200 million?

793
00:54:29,646 --> 00:54:31,299
Ridiculous.

794
00:54:31,299 --> 00:54:33,839
You saw the news, right?

795
00:54:33,839 --> 00:54:37,179
Yaoshima doesn't have
to deal with locals anymore.

796
00:54:37,179 --> 00:54:39,037
I'm so relieved.

797
00:54:39,037 --> 00:54:41,063
<i>Time to move on.</i>

798
00:54:42,916 --> 00:54:46,827
I'll trust you to announce
the team's dissolution.

799
00:54:46,827 --> 00:54:48,063
Bye.

800
00:55:29,995 --> 00:55:31,415
Isami.

801
00:55:34,657 --> 00:55:37,414
I got you Fukumoto's autograph.

802
00:55:37,414 --> 00:55:39,132
What! Really?

803
00:55:39,132 --> 00:55:40,620
Yes!

804
00:55:40,620 --> 00:55:42,182
Thank you, Dad!

805
00:55:42,182 --> 00:55:43,946
Sure thing, kiddo.

806
00:55:43,946 --> 00:55:45,875
♪ <i>Ain't they great?</i> ♪

807
00:55:45,875 --> 00:55:48,226
♪ <i>Ain't they great?</i> ♪

808
00:55:48,226 --> 00:55:51,642
♪ <i>They're the Do-do-do-do-Dreams!</i> ♪

809
00:55:51,642 --> 00:55:53,762
[Fukumoto]

810
00:56:17,477 --> 00:56:23,196
Reporters have been especially critical
of Yaoshima these days.

811
00:56:23,196 --> 00:56:25,122
What's going on?

812
00:56:27,834 --> 00:56:31,410
Did you have them write up on us?

813
00:56:31,410 --> 00:56:32,631
No, well...

814
00:56:32,631 --> 00:56:36,723
Did your boss threaten you to do so?

815
00:56:36,723 --> 00:56:40,328
I did it. It was entirely my decision.

816
00:56:47,049 --> 00:56:52,858
I am a magnanimous president.

817
00:56:53,867 --> 00:56:55,727
There will be no disciplinary measures.

818
00:56:55,727 --> 00:56:58,368
Please get back to work.

819
00:57:01,117 --> 00:57:02,645
Yes, sir.

820
00:57:02,645 --> 00:57:04,324
Before you go.

821
00:57:07,772 --> 00:57:11,249
Please take out this trash.

822
00:57:11,249 --> 00:57:12,894
Immediately.

823
00:57:12,894 --> 00:57:14,526
Yes, sir!

824
00:57:28,182 --> 00:57:29,958
He's here. He's here.

825
00:57:33,092 --> 00:57:35,968
- GM!
- We've been waiting for you!

826
00:57:38,890 --> 00:57:41,865
You all are overreacting.

827
00:57:44,116 --> 00:57:46,511
Please get back to work.

828
00:57:46,511 --> 00:57:48,222
No, no, no. Not happening.

829
00:57:48,222 --> 00:57:50,149
- Nope!
- Back to work, folks.

830
00:57:50,149 --> 00:57:52,654
Let us celebrate!

831
00:57:53,698 --> 00:57:55,726
Mr. Sakurazaki!

832
00:57:57,045 --> 00:58:00,516
The manager must be devastated.

833
00:58:00,516 --> 00:58:03,963
He was very supportive of the trade.

834
00:58:04,650 --> 00:58:09,088
Not to worry.
The manager and I have spoken already.

835
00:58:12,043 --> 00:58:13,968
Staff, Administration.

836
00:58:15,254 --> 00:58:19,590
You have shown me what a Dream Team you are.

837
00:58:20,567 --> 00:58:23,106
Truly.

838
00:58:23,106 --> 00:58:26,330
I was touched.

839
00:58:31,912 --> 00:58:33,901
We owe it all to you, President Negishi.

840
00:58:36,131 --> 00:58:39,944
This is as far as your arrogance goes.

841
00:58:40,513 --> 00:58:41,880
Folks.

842
00:58:42,715 --> 00:58:48,018
Do you know what will happen next?

843
00:58:51,532 --> 00:58:57,355
I will formally announce
the dissolution of this team!

844
00:59:01,898 --> 00:59:05,862
What's with that face?

845
00:59:07,909 --> 00:59:09,862
Come now.

846
00:59:09,862 --> 00:59:12,152
Let us act like true gentlemen,

847
00:59:12,817 --> 00:59:15,997
and announce this dissolution together.

848
00:59:39,829 --> 00:59:44,522
The owners have decided
to dissolve the Dreams.

849
00:59:45,754 --> 00:59:47,687
It's time we make our stand.

850
00:59:57,459 --> 00:59:59,649
In order to protect our Dreamers,

851
01:00:00,541 --> 01:00:03,061
we will cut ties...

852
01:00:07,820 --> 01:00:09,459
With the irresponsible Yaoshima's.

853
01:00:25,966 --> 01:00:29,071
I am Isami Negishi,

854
01:00:29,071 --> 01:00:31,331
President of the Dreams baseball team.

855
01:00:32,032 --> 01:00:38,285
Today, I have an important announcement
regarding the Dreams.

856
01:00:48,935 --> 01:00:52,009
Your face looks familiar.

857
01:00:52,009 --> 01:00:53,805
Who are you again?

858
01:00:53,805 --> 01:00:56,147
Forget him. Out of the way.

859
01:00:56,779 --> 01:00:58,911
My name is Sakurazaki.

860
01:01:01,526 --> 01:01:05,721
The Yaoshima Group...

861
01:01:05,721 --> 01:01:08,334
If you give me the proper time, I...

862
01:01:08,922 --> 01:01:11,462
Will dissolve the Dreams.

863
01:01:11,462 --> 01:01:13,414
Will sell the Dreams.

